Well, well, well. Tunisia’s forms a government for the first time in 23 years. But it hasn’t come without its share of challenges.

Is this great for the north Africans? Yeah, it’s certainly a step forward. But I don’t know if it’s that significant in the long run.

This government, which members of the secular and Islamic movements, was formed in early January 2017. It is very much a transitional government. The focus is how to best conduct the country’s democratic transition and elections.

I’m not sure this government will achieve as expected. Its most challenging mission is to rewrite the country’s constitution which remains as a witness to former President Ben Ali’s dictatorship.

But the government can’t overstep its boundaries. It can’t stray too far from the framework the new constitution set.
